<p><b>Bernard–Soulier syndrome</b> (BSS), also called <b>hemorrhagiparous thrombocytic dystrophy</b>,<sup id="cite_ref-htd_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-htd-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> is a rare <a href="/wiki/Autosomal_recessive" title="Autosomal recessive" class="mw-redirect">autosomal recessive</a> <a href="/wiki/Coagulopathy" title="Coagulopathy">coagulopathy</a> (bleeding disorder) that causes a deficiency of <i><a href="/wiki/Glycoprotein_Ib" title="Glycoprotein Ib">glycoprotein Ib</a></i> (GpIb), the receptor for <a href="/wiki/Von_Willebrand_factor" title="Von Willebrand factor">von Willebrand factor</a>, an important glycoprotein involved in <a href="/wiki/Hemostasis" title="Hemostasis">hemostasis</a>.</p>
<p>The incidence of BSS is estimated to be less than 1 case per million persons, based on cases reported from Europe, North America, and Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>BSS is a <a href="/wiki/Giant_platelet_disorder" title="Giant platelet disorder">giant platelet disorder</a>, meaning that it is characterized by abnormally large platelets.</p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
<div id="toctitle">
